The not-hardwired relationship of interfaces, described at RFC8432 (“…flexible and therefore configured via a management system or controller”) may be configured through the Equipment Model (RFC8438) by setting a read-write node of the model. In this model, to my understanding, the only relevant leaf for such a configuration is the leaf “parent” :

        leaf parent {
          type leafref {
            path "../../component/name";
            require-instance false;
          }
          description
            "The name of the component that physically contains this
             component.

             If this leaf is not instantiated, it indicates that this
             component is not contained in any other component.

            In the event that a physical component is contained by
             more than one physical component (e.g., double-wide
             modules), this node contains the name of one of these
             components.  An implementation MUST use the same name
             every time this node is instantiated.";
          reference
            "[RFC 6933](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6933): Entity MIB (Version 4) - entPhysicalContainedIn";
        }

Note however that the relationship described at RFC8432 between “Ethernet port” and “Radio Link Terminal” is not a contained-in or parent-child relationship, that can fit exactly to the “parent” leaf of the Equipment Model. It is more likely to describe the relationship of these interfaces as a relationship of peer interfaces.

At the RFC8343 interfaces model, the leaf-lists higher-layer-if and lower-layer-if, are read-only nodes, that can be used just to show the interfaces relationships (as it has been mentioned by Daniela too).
Besides this, the RFC8343 has the following relevant statement:

“   While the interface layering is configured in interface-type-specific
   models, two generic state data leaf-lists, "higher-layer-if" and
   "lower-layer-if", represent a read-only view of the interface
   layering hierarchy.”

This issue was mentioned during the [YANGsters meeting in IEEE](https://1.ieee802.org/yangsters-electronic-meeting-agenda-october-24-2023/). Similar issue may appears in other technologies which act as Ethernet bridges: Ethernet-over-OTN and FlexE (is there Ethernet inside Tunnel interfaces?).

IEEE prefers to avoid increasing the `when` to include our `ianaift:microwaveRadioLinkTerminal`.
The proposal was to not modify the `ieee-dot1q-bridge` module and keep the [`when` clause as it is now](https://github.com/YangModels/yang/blob/bb8269aa263e0564ba475fffc4c3174f8994f2b6/standard/ieee/draft/802.1/Qcw/ieee802-dot1q-bridge.yang#L1141) (4 interfaces types).
Our `ianaift:microwaveRadioLinkTerminal` may inherit from `ianaift:ethernetCsmacd` in order to accommodate the `when` clause. That enables the bridge to use it.

```yang
  identity microwaveRadioLinkTerminal {
    base ethernetCsmacd;
    description
      "radio link interface for one or several aggregated microwave carriers.";
    reference
      "RFC XXXX - A YANG Data Model for Microwave Radio Link";
  }
```
Most of the leaves of the `ianaift:ethernetCsmacd` will be irrelevant: `auto-negotiation`, `speed`, `flow-control`, ...
It was said that "It's not unusual to have irrelevant leaves in models."

I am also asking to my Orange colleagues if we have another option.

