Header compression profiles (or modes) are read-only and are declared by the device, according to its capabilities.

The following example (please, check branch eth-compression) describes an interface that supports three different compression modes, the first called "HC-PROFILE-1" compresses the MAC and C-VLAN layer headers, the second called "HC-PROFILE-2" compresses the MAC, C-VLAN, S-VLAN and IPV4 layer headers, the third called HC-PROFILE-3 compresses all the headers included in the first 64 bytes of the ethernet packet. Usually a device compresses either by protocol or by size, but in the example both are reported to be as generic as possible.

The "configured-profile" node selects the profile that the device must operate.
The "enable" node enables/disables header compression.

Devices that only support enabling and disabling the functionality, must not instantiate the "supported-profiles" and "configured-profile" nodes (is this the best practice?).
```
{
	"header-compression": {
		"supported-profiles": [
			{
				"name": "HC-PROFILE-1",
				"protocol-list": {
					"protocols": [
						"ethernet-mac",
						"vlan"
					]
				}
				"mpls-payload-type": "mpls-palyload-none"
			},
			{
				"name": "HC-PROFILE-2",
				"protocol-list": {
					"protocols": [
						"ethernet-mac",
						"vlan",
						"q-in-q",
						"ipv4"
					]
				"mpls-payload-type": "mpls-palyload-ip-o-mpls"
				}
			},
			{
				"name": "HC-PROFILE-3",
				"header-size": {
					"size": 64
				}
			}
		],
		"configured-profile": "HC-PROFILE-2",
		"enable": "true"
	}
}
```

